Ampere's law is expressed by
\begin{equation}
    \oint \mathbf{B} \cdot d\mathbf{l} = \mu_0 i
\end{equation}
where $\mathbf{B}$ is known as magnetic induction or magnetic field. Its unit is weber per metre square or tesla. If magnetic materials are placed in the field of induction, the elementary magnetic dipoles, permanent or induced, will set up their own field that will modify the original field. A large value of $\mathbf{B}$ in an iron core is explained by a subsidiary vector, the magnetization $\mathbf{M}$, which is the magnetic moment per unit volume of the core material. A hypothetical current $i_M$ is introduced and Ampere's law, (1), is modified accordingly:
\begin{equation}
    \oint \mathbf{B} \cdot d\mathbf{l} = \mu_0 (i + i_M)
\end{equation}
Writing
\begin{equation}
    \oint \mathbf{B} \cdot d\mathbf{l} = \mu_0 i + \mu_0 \oint \mathbf{M} \cdot d\mathbf{l}
\end{equation}
we find
\begin{equation}
    \oint \left( \mathbf{B} - \mu_0 \mathbf{M} \right) \cdot d\mathbf{l} = i
\end{equation}
or
\begin{equation}
    \oint \mathbf{H} \cdot d\mathbf{l} = i
\end{equation}
where
\begin{equation}
    \mathbf{H} = \frac{\mathbf{B} - \mu_0 \mathbf{M}}{\mu_0}
\end{equation}
is known as the magnetic field strength. Therefore,
\begin{equation}
    \mathbf{B} = \mu_0 (\mathbf{H} + \mathbf{M})
\end{equation}
The unit of $\mathbf{H}$ is henry per metre.

\begin{itemize}
    \item[(a)] For paramagnetic material, $\mathbf{B}$ is directly proportional to $\mathbf{H}$, the relation being $\mathbf{B} = k_m \mu_0 \mathbf{H}$, where $k_m$ is the permeability of the magnetic medium, which is a constant for a given temperature and density of the material.
    \item[(b)] In ferromagnetic materials, the relationship between $\mathbf{B}$ and $\mathbf{H}$ is far from linear. The $\mathbf{B}$–$\mathbf{H}$ curve is known as the familiar hysteresis curve. $k_m$ is a function not only of the value of $\mathbf{H}$ but also because of hysteresis and is a function of the magnetic and thermal history of the specimen.
\end{itemize}

