\end{align}

(a) Let the electric and magnetic fields be given by:
\begin{align}
    \mathbf{E} &= \mathbf{E}_0 e^{i(\omega t - \mathbf{k} \cdot \mathbf{r} + \phi)} \quad (4) \\
    \mathbf{B} &= \mathbf{B}_0 e^{i(\omega t - \mathbf{k} \cdot \mathbf{r} + \phi)} \quad (5)
\end{align}

Let the wave be propagated in the $z$-direction. Then:
\begin{align*}
    \nabla \cdot \mathbf{E} &= -i \mathbf{k} \cdot \mathbf{E} = 0 \\
    \nabla \cdot \mathbf{B} &= -i \mathbf{k} \cdot \mathbf{B} = 0
\end{align*}

This shows that both $\mathbf{E}$ and $\mathbf{B}$ are perpendicular to $\mathbf{k}$, which is the direction of propagation. Therefore, both $\mathbf{E}$ and $\mathbf{B}$ are transverse oscillations.

(b) $\mathbf{B}$ and $\mathbf{E}$ are in phase.

(c) Using equation (3):
\begin{align*}
    \nabla \times \mathbf{E} &= -i \mathbf{k} \times \mathbf{E} = -i \omega \mathbf{B} \\
    \therefore \mathbf{B} &= \frac{\mathbf{k} \times \mathbf{E}}{\omega} = \frac{1}{c} \frac{\mathbf{k} \times \mathbf{E}}{k} \\
    \therefore \mathbf{B} &= \frac{1}{c} \hat{\mathbf{s}} \times \mathbf{E} \quad (6)
\end{align*}

where $\hat{\mathbf{s}} = \mathbf{k}/k$ is a unit vector in the direction of propagation. The three vectors $\mathbf{E}$, $\mathbf{B}$, and $\mathbf{k}$ form a right-handed rectangular coordinate system. From equation (6), we obtain $\mathbf{B} = \mathbf{E}/c$.

